            <h1>Engineering Microorganisms: Review</h1>
            <p>
                Quick question and answers on engineering microorganisms.
            </p>
            <br>
            <div class="quiz-questions">
                <p class="questions">
                    What are the main steps in the when using microorganisms for production?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            When using microorganisms for production, the following steps are essential:
                        </p>
                            <figure>
                                <img src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/microbesIndustry.pdf">
                                <figcaption>Different kinds of organisms and their applications in industry.</figcaption>
                            </figure>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    Selecting the microbe and modifying the strain for our production. For the selection process, here we should consider:
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>
                                            Adaptibility to simple and inexpensive mediums.
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Quick growth in high temperature environements.
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Good level of production.
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Good resistance to technological stresses; stirring etc.
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Stable genetic traits.
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Compatible behaviour with life in a bioreactor.
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Ease of product recovery; do we have to lyse the cells or is the product secreted?
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Toxicity especially when producing food products.
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Optimising the culture medium, we should make sure that it is apt to the physiology of our selected microbe.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Select our fermentation technology. Scale should be considered here, a beaker vs a 2000 L bioreactor.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Recovering the bioproduct or cells.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    Explain what experimental evolution is, and what the advantages of such a process are for industrial productions.
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            Experimental evolution is the process of guiding the selection of certain organisms for the creation of a useful/desired organism. The advantages in industrial production for such a process are the following:
                        </p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    Product organisms are not considered GMOs, thus can be sold used freely.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    We can optimise our strains to our growth medium.
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        <p>
                            Experimental evolution can be applied for: the production of vaccines, study of resistant bacteria, adapting strains to new conditions etc.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    You would like to produce a vitamin by using a bacteria. This will be for consumption. You start by cloning the genes used in the production of said vitamin, into a plasmid. What are the characteristics taken into consideration of the plasmid used if you wish to directly use the bacteria in this production?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            When using a plasmid for holding genes inside a bacteria for production the following should be taken into account and for the following reasons:
                        </p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    In general the plasmid should be compatible to the host organism. This will depend on the origin of replication and segregation systems used by the host, and even the size of the plasmid.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    The plasmid should be stable inside our host organism. For this we can use one of three systems, toxin/antitoxin (TA system), metablism based systems, or operator repressor titration (ORT) systems.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    The replication and copy number inside our host should be taken into account. We don't want the production to be to feeble nor to too great; should it impact the bacteria's health.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    We should make sure that the plasmid does not have any proteins or elements that might be toxic to the host organism. Moreover the system of selection for this plasmid should be compatible with the host.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What are the different types markers for selection? What difference is there between a comlementation marker and a dominant marker.
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            There are two main types of markers used for selection. Those are:
                        </p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    Complementation or dominant markers: resistance to antibiotics, heavy metals, metabolic markers.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Homologous markers for food grade production.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        <p>
                            The difference between a complementation and a dominant marker is... INCOMPLETE
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What systems allow us to maintain plasmids in our microorganisms when scaling production?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <figure>
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/addictionSys.pdf">
                            <figcaption>Addiction systems for maintaining a plasmid in a microbe during industrial production.</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Toxin/antitoxin (TA):
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        Protein regulated loci.
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        Antisense RNA regulated.
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        Restriction modfication.
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Metabolism based:
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        Catabolism based.
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        Anabolism based.
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Operator repressor titration (ORT).
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <p>
                            Plasmid addiction systems are used in order to maintain a plasmid during production. There are three types of plasmid addiction systems they are shown in the figure.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    Explain what genome editing is.
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            Genome editing is the process of actively modifying one or more genetic sequences in an organism. Molecular tools must be used (different from experimental evolution) to manipulate the genome. Such tools are: TALEN, CRISPR, and MAGE.
                        </p>
                        <p class="warning">
                            MAGE is not necessarily a targetted method, but it does require the use of molecular tools. Thus it is a genome editing tool.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What are the main steps in a fermentation production? What parameters can be taken into account and or controlled?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            A fermentation process is a multistep system, it can be complex but simply put it involves the following:
                        </p>
                        <figure>
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/fermentationProcess.pdf">
                            <figcaption>The fermentation process requires a multitude of variables but the main goal is to grow a microbe which will produce a product for us.</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Sterlising our materials, including the reactors (seed reactor and production reactor) and the culture medium.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Placing the innoculum and culture medium into the reactor.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Centrifuging/filtering the product of reaction.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Recovering the surnatant and the biomass. 
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Purifying and extracting the product.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <p>
                            During production there are a number of variables to consider inside of the reactor, including: temperature, airation/agitation, foam prevention, pH levels, O<sub>2</sub> & CO<sub>2</sub> levels, finally the time of the reaction.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What are the different methods for quantifying biomass?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            Biomass can be assessed in a few different ways.
                        </p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Gravimetry g/L mesured by weight.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Optical density UDO/mL (turbidometry or nephelemetry).
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Other UFC/mL (hematimetry (Thoma cell), bioluminescence (ATPase activity), cytometry, or simply counting).
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <p>
                            The mathematics behind the measure are the folowing. We should know the number of generations, and the number of cells. 
                        </p>
                        <table>
                            <tr>
                                <td>n</td>
                                <td>0</td>
                                <td>1</td>
                                <td>2</td>
                                <td>3</td>
                                <td>4</td>
                                <td>5</td>
                                <td>6</td>
                                <td>7</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td rowspan="2">X</td>
                                <td>1</td>
                                <td>2</td>
                                <td>4</td>
                                <td>8</td>
                                <td>16</td>
                                <td>32</td>
                                <td>64</td>
                                <td>128</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>2<sup>0</sup></td>
                                <td>2<sup>1</sup></td>
                                <td>2<sup>2</sup></td>
                                <td>2<sup>3</sup></td>
                                <td>2<sup>4</sup></td>
                                <td>2<sup>5</sup></td>
                                <td>2<sup>6</sup></td>
                                <td>2<sup>7</sup></td>
                            </tr>
                        </table>
                        <p>
                            The growth of cells happens in the following way for bacteria (scissiparity). As shown in the table above, note that n is the number of generations, and X is the number of cells. the number of cells can be expressed as a power of a number of generations.
                        </p>
                        <div class="mathsFormulas">
                            $$
                                X_t = 2^n X_0
                            $$
                            $$
                                \ln{X_t} = n \ln{2} + \ln{X_0}
                            $$
                            $$
                                n = t/G
                            $$
                            $$
                                \ln{X_t} = t \ln{2}/G + \ln{X_0}
                            $$
                            $$
                                V = k[X] = \frac{dX}{dt} = \int^X_{X_0} \frac{dX}{X} = \int^t_{t_0} k \cdot dt
                            $$
                            $$
                                \ln{X} = \ln{X_0} + kt
                            $$
                        </div>
                        <p>
                            k is the speed constant of the growth. 
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What parameters influence growth?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <figure>
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/fissionScissiparity.png">
                            <figcaption>Exponential growth of microorganisms.</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                        <p>
                            Growth can be influenced by a number of parameters both external and internal to the organism used. One internal characteristic to take into account is the generation time of an organism.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Moreover different species can divide in different ways, bacteria generally do so by fission or scissiparity whereby one bacteria gives birth to two identical daughter cells (15 - 60 mins). Yeast do so by budding, the mother cell gives off smaller daughter cells one at a time generally (45 - 120 mins). Fungii filament (4 - 8 h).
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What is a batch culture? What are the advantages of such a method; and the disadvantages?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            Batch culture is a discontinous culture. Whereby the substrate is introduced at once in the begining, and then the reaction is run. The system is closed for the duration of the reaction. Once finished, the products are removed the bioreactor is cleaned and the process is started again.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The advantages of a batch culture are the following:
                        </p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                The reaction volume remains constant.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                The biomass increases as per the growth curve. The substrate is consumed and a product appears.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                There is no loss of microorganisms.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                There is little to no chance of contamination (reactions tend to be short).
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Flexible method can be adapted to many industries.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <p>
                            The disadvantages of this method are the following:
                        </p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Costly materials and reactors.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Difficult to sterilise the materials, requires large quantities of water.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Productivity is low this is linked to the type of reactor used (wasted time between reactions).
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Productivity is low because of the culture (long waits during cell growth).
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Difficult to reproduce exactly the same.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What is the fed-batch method? What is it used for?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            In the fed-batch method the substrate is introduced but without removing the previous the previous substrate. The advantages of this method are:
                        </p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                The initial volume is small so the growth happens at a constant rate while the substrate is being added. Growth is faster.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                The volume increases little by little, along with the biomass.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                There is a possibility to modify the composition of the medium as needed.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Alows for the orientation of the organisms metabolism if needed and to then stimulate the production of the metabolite after growth.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Possibility to increase the concentration in substrate to levels that would be inhibiting to growth, had they been introduced at the begining of growth.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <p>
                            Fed-batch cultures are great for industrial applications, where the levels of a nutrient are susceptible to have a retarding effect on the growth of our strains. A typical example of use is when working with yeast, in order to avoid the production of ethanol, which can harm their later production, sugar is added progressively. This will stimulate growth but not allow for the production of ethanol.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What is a chemostat reactor? What are the advantages/disadvantages?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <figure>
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/bioreactorChemostat.jpg">
                            <figcaption>Illustration of a chemostat reactor. The reaction is done continously and the media is simultaneously added and removed.</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                        <p>
                            Chemostat culture is a reactor where the substrate is introduced and some of the system (products) is removed at the same time. The advantages disadvantages of this system are:
                        </p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                The culture is homogenous, microbe population is constant and in a state of growth.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Transformation of substrates can be done indefinitely.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Products are recovered little by little as they are produced.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Productivity is much higher, the reactor never has to be emptied.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                The reactor is used 24 h a day, economically it is much more interesting.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Allows for evolution of our strains this can be an advantage as our strains might adapt to better suit the reactor.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <p>
                            The disadvantages are:
                        </p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Contamination can be a problem.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                There is a possibility for the initial strain to be lost.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Formation of a biofilm can happen, thus mutations may form.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Denaturation might inactivate proteins needed.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                There is no possibility to produce secondary metabolites, such as antibiotics, as the first product is immediately removed from the reactor as it is produced.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <p>
                            The chemostat culture can b used for the study of microbes, to study their kinetics, and the evolution of strains.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What is a "bilan carbone"?
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <div class="mathsFormula">
                            $$
                                1 \, Glucose \rightarrow 2 \, lactate + 2 \, ATP
                            $$
                        </div>
                        <p>
                            Carbon "bilan", or balance refers to the efficiency at which carbon was taken and converted to useful product. In order to calculate this we need to know a few different things: what molecule we are giving for use as a substrate (how many carbon atoms), what molecule we are trying to produce (number of carbon), and the stiochiometry that joins the two. This should allow us to calculate the percent of carbon that was taken from our substrate and put into our product. If the balance is less than 100% this indicates that there is another molecule being produced. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We can see that 1 glucose molecule is used in the production of 2 lactates and 2 ATP molecules. 
                        </p>
                    </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    What are the different systems for cloning that you know? Explain the concepts.
                </p>
                    <!-- <button class="collapsible">View Solution</button> -->
                    <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                        <p>
                            I know of 9 different methods for editing genes, they act in three different ways: 3 are DNA, 2 RNA, and 4 protein based. Shown below:
                        </p>
                        <figure>
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/genomeEditors.png">
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/genomeEditors.pdf">
                            <figcaption>9 Different genome editors, 3 different functions. Source: <a href="https://youtu.be/Wswvf8Nrubg" target="_blank">Genomic Editing Revolution - Prof. George Church</a></figcaption>
                        </figure>
                        <p>
                            Although the classical ones are the following:
                        </p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Digestion and ligation.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                PCR Fusion based systems.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                GIBSON.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                In-Fusion (LIC).
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                SLICE.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Gateway cloning (&lambda;<sub>red</sub>).
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    <div class="mini-header">Digestion/Religation</div>
                        <figure>
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/cloningDigestionReligation.png">
                            <figcaption>Here EcoR1 is used to cut and clone a gene of interest into a plasmid; the same enzyme is used both times which produces sticky ends since EcoR1 leaves overhangs.</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                        <p>
                            For digestion religation; there are 3 types of restriction enzymes. They each work differently.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Type I</strong> Recognises a specific sequence, then tracks down 1000 - 5000 bases before cutting only one of the strands, 75 nucleotides are release where the cut is made. A second endonuclease is required to cut the complimentary strand. This should leave hanging ends which can be used for hybridisation.
                        </p>
                        <p class="inline-foot-note">
                            Requires Mg<sup>2+</sup>, ATP, and S-Adenosyl Methionine (SAM).
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Type II:</strong> Recognises a specific target sequence in the DNA then makes a break in both strands at or close to the recognition site. 
                        </p>
                        <p class="inline-foot-note">
                            Usually requires Mg<sup>2+</sup>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Type III:</strong> Has intermediate properties between I and II. It breaks both strands of DNA at a specific distance from the recognition site.
                        </p>
                        <p class="inline-foot-note">
                            Requires Mg<sup>2+</sup> and ATP.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            There are various disadvantages associated to this method. Such as:
                        </p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                Not very effective, low efficiency when transformed.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Scars are left.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                Dependant on the enzyme and cloning site in question.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    <div class="mini-header">Fusion PCR</div>
                        <figure>
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/temp_fusionPCR.png">
                            <figcaption>PCR amplification, for the creation of homologous sequences is capital to the functioning of this method. Tedious, but works quite well.</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                        <p>
                            PCR based fusion is the use of PCR and sequences with overlapping homologous parts. Once amplification elongation etc happens, these parts become fused at their overlapping sequences. Note that this system can also be used to delete parts of a plasmid. Homologous parts should be a minimum of 15 bp long; this can vary depending on GC content. This method relies on <em>E. coli's</em> recombinase activity for religating the strands.
                        </p>
                        <div class="warning">
                            A polymerase without displacement activity is used!
                        </div>
                        <p>
                            The plasmid is nicked, both strands are broken, Dpnl will digest the parent plasmid, finally after transformation the nicks are repaired by the host.
                        </p>
                        <div class="warning">
                            Dpn1 is a type II restriction enzyme which digest methylated DNA; in our case the newly produced (PCR) DNA is not methylated and is thus untouched. The parent sequences are digested and eliminated leaving only the modified strands.
                        </div>
                        <p>
                            PCR cloning will be affected by various different factors. Such as the number of cycles done during the reaction, or the length of the insert used.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Using this system we can either insert sequences or even delte them by creating the correct strands for PCR use.
                        </p>
                    <div class="mini-header">SLiCE (Seamless ligation cloning extract)</div>
                        <blockquote>
                            <p>
                                We describe a novel cloning method termed SLiCE (Seamless Ligation Cloning Extract) that utilizes easy to generate bacterial cell extracts to assemble multiple DNA fragments into recombinant DNA molecules in a single in vitro recombination reaction. SLiCE overcomes the sequence limitations of traditional cloning methods, facilitates seamless cloning by recombining short end homologies (15bp) with or without flanking heterologous sequences and provides an effective strategy for directional subcloning of DNA fragments from Bacteria Artificial Chromosomes (BACs) or other sources. SLiCE is highly cost effective as a number of standard laboratory bacterial strains can serve as sources for SLiCE extract. In addition, the cloning efficiencies and capabilities of these strains can be greatly improved by simple genetic modifications. As an example, we modified the DH10B Escherichia coli strain to express an optimized j prophage Red recombination system. This strain, termed PPY, facilitates SLiCE with very high efficiencies and demonstrates the versatility of the method.
                            </p>
                            <p class="quote-author">
                                <a class="foot-note" data-href="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/docs/2012_SLiCE A novel bacterial cell extract-based DNA cloning method.pdf">SLiCE: Zhang <em>et al.</em> 2012</a>
                            </p>
                        </blockquote>
                        <figure>
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/temp_slice.png">
                            <figcaption>Multiple cloning methods are possible by SLiCE; simply put what it is, is a reaction medium that will catalyse our reaction.</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                        <p>
                            This method allows for recombineering <em>in vitro</em>. Transformation is done into chemocompetent cells by electroporation. The steps for this process are to add homologous ends to a sequence of interest (overlap with target sequence). Then linearise the plasmid, and add RecA<sup>-</sup> bacterial extract which allows for the ligation. 
                        </p>
                        <p class="warning">
                            This whole process happens in vitro, the last part is transformation into <em>E. coli</em>.
                        </p>
                    <div class="mini-header">Gibson Cloning</div>
                        <figure>
                            <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/micro_biobuilderGibsonAssembly.pdf">
                            <figcaption>From BioBuilder (2015).</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                        <blockquote>
                            <p>
                                Developed by Dr. Daniel Gibson at the J. Craig Venter Institute during their work on full genome assembly, the Gibson technique uses PCR to prepare multiple DNA fragments for simultaneous assembly.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Gibson assembly has several advantages over both traditional cloning and BioBrick assembly methods, the greatest of which might be its usefulness for assembling many DNA parts simultaneously. Even in its earliest stage of development, a single Gibson assembly reaction can piece together about ten DNA parts.
                            </p>
                            <p class="quote-author">
                                <a class="foot-note" data-href="http://derecksnotes.com/owncloud/index.php/s/S6aWeucrBGN3Snr" target="_blank">BioBuilder (2015)</a>
                            </p>
                        </blockquote>
                        <p>
                            Gibson cloning is the insertion of a sequence into a plasmid. It is done in <em>in vitro</em> in the following way. First homologous regions are added to our gene of interest by PCR. Then these two strands with homologous parts, the gene of interest and the vector, are partially digested (thermolabile T5 exonuclease) to produce complimentary overhanging sections. Finally ligation is done by a Taq ligase, to produce a single strand. This strand can then be transformed into <em>E. coli</em>. Multiple fragments can be cloned at once.
                        </p>
                        <blockquote>
                            <p>
