                        Generally yes the presence of urease is undesirable as it produces CO<sub>2</sub> and ammonia which is toxic to mammals. Although urease can be found in humans and mammals, they do not produce it themselves, it is produces by bacteria found on the bodies of these organisms, speficically the intenstines.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <p class="questions">
                    Explain the functioning of both systems of induction NICE and ZitR in <em>L. lactis</em>.
                </p>
                <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                    <p>
                        NICE stands for Nisine controlled gene expression. It is a method for the controlled expression of proteins in lactic bacteria.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/micro_NiceSystem.pdf">
                        <figcaption>Nisine controlled gene expression system; works through signal transduction.</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        <strong>NICE Mechanism:</strong> The way the NICE system works is the following:
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            Nisin binds to NisK transmembranary receptor protein.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            NisK phosphorylates NisR.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            NisR-P fixes the gene promotor, and induces expression.
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
                <figure>
                    <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/micro_geneExpressionZitR.pdf">
                    <figcaption>ZitR or Zinc-Responsive Repressor expression system.</figcaption>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    <strong>ZitR or Zinc-Responsive Repressor</strong>, is also a method for controlling gene expression in lactic bacteria; it works in the following way: 
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Zn<sup>2+</sup> is in excess:</strong> ZitR is complexed with Zn<sup>2+</sup> and thus fixed on before the zitR sequence before our gene of interest.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Zn<sup>2+</sup> starvation:</strong> ZitR is inactive and thus the RNA polymerase can fix itself to the promotor and transcribe our gene of interest.
                    </li>
                </ol>
                <p class="questions">
                    How can we stick on proteins to the surface of a lactic bacteria?
                </p>
                <div class="collapseContentDisabled">
                    <p>
                        Lactic bacteria can be used in healthcare, they are generally non-toxic, and are GRAS. Moreover lactic bacteria have probiotic qualities. It is for this reason they can be used for human healthcare; we can make them even better by sticking proteins to the surface of these organisms in order to give them new properties and interaction with the immune system.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        There a few different methods for anchoring proteins to the surface of a lactic bacteria:
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <img class="lazy" data-src="/courses/documents/engineering-microorganisms/micro_anchoringMethodsLacticBacteria.pdf">
                        <figcaption>Illustration of the 5 different anchoring methods to the cellular surface of a lactic bacteria.</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            Transmembranary anchor.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Lipoprotein anchor.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            LPXTG domain.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            AcmA domain (3 motifs LysM) which link covalently to the peptidoglycan layer of gram+ bacteria; method used in the production of vaccines.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Surface protein sticks on the S layer (surface of the peptidoglycan layer) of the cell.
                        </li>
                    </ol>
